01:33.677 --> 01:36.388
♪ I'm awesome, a quarter
of my life gone by. ♪

01:38.265 --> 01:40.559
♪ I'm awesome. ♪

01:43.144 --> 01:44.980
-Hey, how are you?
-Good, how are you?

01:44.980 --> 01:47.232
-Good.
-Frank. Subbing for a few days.

01:47.232 --> 01:48.984
-I'm Gerry, Frank. Listen, I
just saw where you parked.

01:48.984 --> 01:51.028
But, we have a handicap spot
right up front.

01:51.028 --> 01:53.530
-I appreciate that, but I just
want to be treated like everyone
else.

01:53.530 --> 01:55.657
So, regular parking's fine for
me.
-Alright.

01:55.657 --> 01:58.118
Well let me get the door for ya.
-I got it.

01:58.118 --> 02:00.746
-Okay, well I'll...
-[Frank]: No.

02:00.746 --> 02:03.582
Look at the picture. Do I look
like I'm in a wheelchair?

02:03.582 --> 02:06.877
-No, you don't.
-No. After you.

02:06.877 --> 02:09.797
-Alright, thanks Frank,
see you later.

02:09.797 --> 02:12.967
♪ Music ♪

02:12.967 --> 02:15.094
-Sir, you can't be on
your cell phone.

02:15.094 --> 02:16.929
-It's school business.
-It's a policy here.

02:16.929 --> 02:18.346
We're not allowed
phone calls, Sir.

02:18.346 --> 02:20.181
-I understand that but
it's official school business.

02:20.181 --> 02:22.893
-He's not allowed to talk.
-Please don't do that.

02:22.893 --> 02:24.770
-He's not allowed to be
on the phone.
-Yeah, no, okay.

02:24.770 --> 02:26.939
-Okay, see you later George.
Thanks, I gotta go.

02:26.939 --> 02:29.108
-No, that's not me. That's...
-No it is, I'm taking off now.

02:29.108 --> 02:31.151
-I'm going to call you right
back, I'll call you right back.

02:31.151 --> 02:34.404
-Aren't you a little old
to be a hall monitor?
-Oh, that's funny.

02:34.404 --> 02:37.992
You are talking to the principal
of this establishment,
my friend.

02:37.992 --> 02:40.119
And I'd like to know what
you're doing in my school

02:40.119 --> 02:42.121
wearing in a suit when there's
children running around?

02:42.121 --> 02:44.873
-I'm with the school board.
-So you know I'm not the...

02:44.873 --> 02:46.541
-Principal?
-Yeah.

02:46.541 --> 02:48.752
-Yeah.
-You can talk on your phone.

02:48.752 --> 02:51.839
But you gotta make it less
obvious. I hide in the corner.

02:51.839 --> 02:54.382
Talk like that.
-Thanks for the tip there Mr...?

02:54.382 --> 02:56.301
-Dwyer. Paul Dwyer.

02:56.301 --> 02:59.262
-Oh! You're Paul Dwyer?
-I am.

02:59.262 --> 03:01.640
-I've heard a lot of good
things about you.
-Yeah.

03:01.640 --> 03:04.518
Anyway I've got to go,
I'm late for a meeting, see you.

03:04.518 --> 03:06.937
-Keep up the charity
work, there, Paul.

03:06.937 --> 03:08.856
-Thank you all for your
patience.

03:08.856 --> 03:11.190
Just a couple more things and
I'll get you out of here.

03:11.190 --> 03:13.735
-[Whispers]: I heard this was
optional, so...slide over.

03:13.735 --> 03:15.654
-[Bobbi]: No.
-Slide over.
-[Bobbi]: No, there's no room.

03:15.654 --> 03:17.739
-Simon, just let me...slide
over a little. Just slide over!

03:17.739 --> 03:22.119
-No! No!
-Nice of you to join
us, Mr. Duncan.

03:22.119 --> 03:24.621
-Hey, I want to talk to you
about volleyball.
-No! Not now.

03:24.621 --> 03:27.290
-Alright, just one last piece
of business. Paul?

03:27.290 --> 03:30.878
-I've been thinking, this
season, let's try to expand
the recycling program.

03:30.878 --> 03:33.421
-[Quietly]: Why don't we just
pull up the football field and
plant a bunch of trees, Paul?

03:33.421 --> 03:38.301
-So, I put bins together.
You got some for plastic,
cardboard, glass, Styrofoam.

03:38.301 --> 03:41.847
-Ah, did you put a bin together
for regular garbage, Paul?

03:41.847 --> 03:45.684
Like, ah, food and napkins?
-That's called compost.

03:45.684 --> 03:47.352
[Laughter]

03:48.269 --> 03:52.273
-Yes! Okay, up top.

03:52.273 --> 03:55.152
-All right, I think that about
covers it. Teach hard everyone.

03:55.152 --> 03:58.864
Alright, Mr. Duncan, Ms. Mason,
my office, 20 minutes.

03:58.864 --> 04:01.449
-For, for?
-[Simon]: Ooooh!

04:01.449 --> 04:05.620
-You done?
-Yes, yes I am done.

04:05.620 --> 04:07.998
[Malik humming]
-Mr. Malik!

04:07.998 --> 04:12.127
-I have this name.
-The grass outside is
looking shaggy.

04:12.127 --> 04:14.171
You need to go outside
and deal with it.

04:14.171 --> 04:18.383
-I will cut plants.
But first...

04:18.383 --> 04:20.761
[Yawns loudly]

04:23.638 --> 04:25.599
Malik take break.

04:29.477 --> 04:33.232
-Morning Robert. Cracking the
whip early this morning?

04:33.232 --> 04:36.276
Without any success
I might add.
-How so?

04:36.276 --> 04:39.029
That was successful.
Malik knows who's in charge.

04:39.029 --> 04:44.451
-Yeah, Callaghan.
-Yeah, and when Callaghan's
not here. It's me. Okay?

04:44.451 --> 04:49.289
-Oh Robert. To be a great leader
you need to inspire fear.

04:49.289 --> 04:52.667
Callaghan is effective because
people are afraid of him.

04:52.667 --> 04:55.254
No one's afraid of you Robert.
-Oh is that so?

04:55.254 --> 04:58.966
Because I swear on all known
Gods I will rip your head off

04:58.966 --> 05:01.843
your body and use it as a tennis
ball for my pure enjoyment.

05:01.843 --> 05:05.513
-If you don't get your finger
out of my face, I'm gonna
have to break it.

05:05.513 --> 05:08.976
-Can I try one again
without the finger?
-Nope.

05:08.976 --> 05:10.936
You missed a spot.

05:11.853 --> 05:13.855
♪ Music ♪

05:13.855 --> 05:16.483
-Hey Frank.
-Hey.

05:18.860 --> 05:21.822
-Frank, you know we have an
elevator right here?

05:23.698 --> 05:27.244
-Are you stupid? Pretend you
don't see the crutches.

05:27.244 --> 05:29.537
Please, Gerry!
-I don't see them.

05:29.537 --> 05:32.373
-See ya Gerry.
-See ya.

05:32.373 --> 05:34.960
♪ Music ♪

05:34.960 --> 05:37.796
-Gerry Duncan, Lisa Mason. Jody
Green from the school board.

05:37.796 --> 05:42.009
-Gerry Duncan? Not Paul Dwyer?
-Sir, Mr. Brown here was...

05:42.009 --> 05:45.887
-Mr. Green.
-Oh God. Ah, Gerry.

05:45.887 --> 05:48.556
What did I say? What did I say?
What did I do? What did I say?

05:48.556 --> 05:51.601
-You said Mr. Brown, but I'm
Mr. Green.

05:51.601 --> 05:56.982
Mr. Green here was on his
cell phone and I thought
he was lurking.

05:56.982 --> 05:59.818
-Yes, I met the
principal earlier.

05:59.818 --> 06:02.321
-I do a lot of, I do a lot of
impersonations.

06:02.321 --> 06:04.698
-It's really nice to meet you,
Mr. Green.

06:04.698 --> 06:07.534
-It's a pleasure, Ms. Mason.
-[Lisa]: Yeah, love to hear more
about that.

06:07.534 --> 06:09.828
-Okay, you know what?
Why are we here?
-Please sit down.

06:11.579 --> 06:14.666
I just wanted to give you guys a
head's up that Jody is going to

06:14.666 --> 06:17.252
be evaluating you both,
the next couple of days.

06:17.252 --> 06:20.463
The board likes to evaluate
all new teachers the
first couple of years.

06:20.463 --> 06:23.884
Just to make sure you're off to
a good start. It's standard.

06:23.884 --> 06:25.760
-What happens if we get a
bad evaluation?

06:25.760 --> 06:28.847
-Well, you might have
to do additional
qualification courses.

06:28.847 --> 06:30.891
Or! You could always get fired.

06:30.891 --> 06:33.476
-Fi...Fired?

06:33.476 --> 06:35.729
Sir, that's ridiculous,
one persons...

06:35.729 --> 06:38.190
What if he has a different
teaching style than I do?

06:38.190 --> 06:41.985
And I have a very modern
approach that the kids
can relate to.

06:41.985 --> 06:44.196
It's not in any books or
anything.

06:44.196 --> 06:47.157
-As long as you're aware
of the paradigm shifts taking
place in the education world.

06:47.157 --> 06:50.035
You should be okay.
-Yeah.

06:50.035 --> 06:53.496
-Obviously, we all do that.
So, it's good.

06:53.496 --> 06:56.124
-Good. Mike.
-Jody.

06:56.124 --> 06:58.585
-[Jody]: I look forward to
seeing your class, Ms. Mason.

06:58.585 --> 07:00.212
-[Lisa]: Yes.
-[Jody]: Lovely to meet you.

07:00.212 --> 07:01.588
-I'm very excited. Thank you.

07:01.588 --> 07:03.382
-[Callaghan]: Alright then.

07:03.382 --> 07:06.051
-He's so nice.
-It's because he smiled at you.

07:06.051 --> 07:08.762
Come on, Sir, we're going to let
one person decide our fate here?

07:08.762 --> 07:11.514
This is ridiculous.
-Duncan, look, listen...

07:11.514 --> 07:16.937
I like you. I really do.
Despite all your shortcomings.

07:16.937 --> 07:20.690
But I gotta tell you if he gives
you a poor evaluation I'll have
no choice,

07:20.690 --> 07:23.110
but to accept the board's
recommendation.

07:23.110 --> 07:25.820
You have to bring your A game.
-Okay.

07:25.820 --> 07:27.822
Sir, I saw you were looking
right at me there.

07:27.822 --> 07:30.951
So now let's give Lisa
her little speech.

07:30.951 --> 07:35.580
-Okay, thanks.
-Thank you. Great opportunity.

07:35.580 --> 07:38.625
-[Callaghan]: It is.
-How come I got a
one on one speech?

07:38.625 --> 07:40.543
But how come?

07:40.543 --> 07:45.548
♪ Music ♪

07:45.548 --> 07:48.051
-[Trudy]: Hi Norman.

07:48.051 --> 07:52.097
Nice to have you back.
How was your stress leave?

07:52.097 --> 07:55.434
-I do feel better.
-Good.

07:55.434 --> 07:59.479
Well, bienvenue chez nous.
-I teach French.

07:59.479 --> 08:03.066
I don't speak it.
Capiche?!

08:03.066 --> 08:05.860
-Yup.
-Gym teachers.

08:07.321 --> 08:10.031
-Wow.
-Oh, he's much better.

08:10.031 --> 08:13.994
So, you and Craig, you left him,
what is this nine times?

08:13.994 --> 08:16.788
-No, it's eight but it's
different now because
I feel like...

08:16.788 --> 08:20.000
-Ms. Galka, my office. Now!
-...he really hears me now.

08:20.000 --> 08:23.586
Right? So nine, eight who
cares right? At that point
it doesn't...

08:23.586 --> 08:26.047
-Bobbi!
-What?

08:26.047 --> 08:28.633
-I asked if I could see you
in my office, please!

08:28.633 --> 08:31.052
-Ugh, I'm kind of busy
right now.

08:31.052 --> 08:35.182
But why don't you just drop by
my phys-ed office if you need
to talk to me? God.

08:35.182 --> 08:37.517
And I think that's a big step.
-It's a date!

08:37.517 --> 08:39.769
-And I feel like, sometimes when
he doesn't hear me

08:39.769 --> 08:42.147
it makes me
want to like...shake him!

08:42.147 --> 08:46.943
-Alright, special visitor today,
Mr. Green, from the board of
education.

08:46.943 --> 08:52.324
Who is here to assess and
observe my teaching style.

08:52.324 --> 08:57.329
And perhaps pass on some of the
ways I teach to future
generations of younger teachers.

08:57.329 --> 09:00.999
So, thank you Mr. Green.
It is an honor to be
chosen for this project.

09:00.999 --> 09:03.251
Actually I'm here to
evaluate Mr. Duncan.

09:03.251 --> 09:06.004
And make sure he's progressing
properly as a new teacher.

09:06.004 --> 09:08.507
-I'm not really new. I've been
subbing for years. So...

09:08.507 --> 09:12.427
-Right.
-Well what happens if Mr. Duncan
gets a bad review?

09:12.427 --> 09:14.262
-Well then we probably just
get a new teacher.

09:14.262 --> 09:16.931
[Class laughs]
-Get out, Jimmy.

09:16.931 --> 09:19.142
-I'm just kidding.
-Out.

09:19.142 --> 09:21.978
Insubordination, I do not
tolerate. So write that down.

09:21.978 --> 09:25.148
-[Jody]: Where does he go?
-I don't know. He's a big boy,
he'll make his own choices.

09:25.148 --> 09:28.902
-What if he gets hit by a car?
-Then that's a bad choice. Okay.

09:28.902 --> 09:30.904
-I'm going to go to the back
of the class now.
-[Gerry]: Okay.

09:30.904 --> 09:33.031
-If I could just get a students
notebook or something.

09:33.031 --> 09:36.243
-[Gerry]: Yeah, not his. That's
not the one we want to take.

09:36.243 --> 09:37.411
Maya, can I borrow your
notebook?

09:37.411 --> 09:38.953
-I'm actually using this for
a class.

09:38.953 --> 09:41.164
-Maya, can I just borrow that?
Uhah, not using it.

09:41.164 --> 09:43.542
-Thank you, I think.
-[Maya]: No problem.

09:43.542 --> 09:46.461
-A lot of that is information
I've given her from my lessons.

09:46.461 --> 09:50.590
That are very prepared.
Alright, let's pick up things
from last class.

09:50.590 --> 09:52.551
Where were we in our lesson?

09:52.551 --> 09:55.387
-You were telling us about your
first high school girlfriend.

09:55.387 --> 09:58.557
You and Bethany hit a rough
patch.
[Gerry]: We hit a rough patch.

09:58.557 --> 10:00.850
So the story continues...
-Sorry, is this part of
today's lesson?

10:00.850 --> 10:03.437
-The start, I always do a
little story, so...

10:03.437 --> 10:07.815
But Bethany, let me tell you
about the break up because,
totally her fault.

10:07.815 --> 10:13.071
-Sorry, ah, I'm going to need to
get your course syllabus
and your lesson plans.

10:13.071 --> 10:16.575
If I can get that tomorrow?
-Tomor...tomorrow?

10:16.575 --> 10:19.786
One day.
♪ Music ♪

10:24.082 --> 10:27.001
-Wow, you're still at it?
-Yeah.

10:27.001 --> 10:30.088
I gotta have short term lesson
plans, long term lesson plans.

10:30.088 --> 10:33.216
It's a lot of work.
-Didn't you already have a
lesson planned?

10:33.216 --> 10:35.594
-Not written down, Bill.
In my head.

10:35.594 --> 10:37.220
That's where my lessons
are when I teach.

10:37.220 --> 10:40.056
They are in my head.
But now I have to
write them on paper

10:40.056 --> 10:42.392
for this evaluator.
Why do I explain this to you?

10:42.392 --> 10:43.977
-Are you the only one getting
evaluated?

10:43.977 --> 10:46.229
-No, Lisa too, but she's got
nothing to worry about.

10:46.229 --> 10:48.773
-She's so hot. What's her deal?
-Bill.

10:48.773 --> 10:50.817
-Is she single? Or...?

10:52.193 --> 10:54.654
-Are you done?
I gotta finish this.

10:54.654 --> 10:56.615
-Why don't you try being
a good teacher?
-I am a good teacher.

10:56.615 --> 10:59.367
I'm a very good teacher.
Now, get out of here.

10:59.367 --> 11:02.496
-Right, well I gotta wake up
late tomorrow, so I'm going to
get that started.

11:02.496 --> 11:03.871
-You want to leave Lisa's number
on the fridge?

11:03.871 --> 11:05.165
-You have no chance
with Lisa, Bill.

11:05.165 --> 11:08.460
She's not your type.
She has ambition.

11:12.005 --> 11:14.424
High five for yourself.

11:16.801 --> 11:18.928
-Mr. Leung!
-Yeah.

11:23.016 --> 11:25.935
Begin.

11:25.935 --> 11:31.149
-Mr. Leung this library's
being run as little more
than a social club.

11:31.149 --> 11:34.152
And it will stop.
Do you understand me?

11:34.152 --> 11:37.738
-This library facility
is being run perfectly.

11:39.282 --> 11:43.453
-Is that so?
-You are so weak.

11:45.664 --> 11:49.417
-Wayne, everyone's so
intimidated by you.

11:49.417 --> 11:53.921
How do I do that?
-Fear is from within.

11:53.921 --> 11:56.883
Other's must doubt themselves
in your presence.

11:56.883 --> 11:59.594
-But how do I implement that?

11:59.594 --> 12:04.723
-[Loud whisper]: Your mother and
your father never loved you.

12:04.723 --> 12:06.643
-Have you been
reading my diar...

12:06.643 --> 12:09.354
You're doing it now.

12:09.354 --> 12:12.106
-Get out of my library,
you idiot.

12:12.106 --> 12:16.403
-Thank you.
Dumb eyes.

12:19.406 --> 12:22.242
-Bobbi, I don't want to coach
little girls' basketball
anymore.

12:22.242 --> 12:26.120
Simon can handle it himself.
-No, you are not having the
senior boys volleyball team.

12:26.120 --> 12:29.040
Okay? The girls like you
and you didn't even win
one game last year.

12:29.040 --> 12:31.125
-We won a game.
-Okay, one game.

12:31.125 --> 12:33.294
-So what, did you see
the team I have?

12:34.921 --> 12:37.465
-How's your evaluation going?
-Oh, I don't know.

12:37.465 --> 12:38.883
-He can be pretty tough.
-I know.

12:38.883 --> 12:41.344
-He gave me a pretty hard
evaluation last year.

12:41.344 --> 12:44.013
Can't imagine how bad yours
is going to be.

12:44.013 --> 12:46.765
-Oh, is that right?
-Yeah.

12:49.185 --> 12:53.064
-Hey, Mr. Green? Here's the
stuff you were looking for.
-Thank you.

12:53.064 --> 12:55.233
-Okay, well...
-[Dwyer]: Uh-oh,
here comes trouble.

12:55.233 --> 12:58.152
-[Jody]: Hey! Look at this.
-[Dwyer]: How you doin' bro?

12:58.152 --> 12:59.613
-How are you?
-[Dwyer]: Good to see you.

12:59.613 --> 13:00.697
-[Gerry]: Good, good.

13:00.697 --> 13:02.156
-Haven't seen you in a while,

13:02.156 --> 13:04.117
since your evaluation.

13:04.117 --> 13:06.536
You know, this guys a legend at
the board? You need to know.

13:06.536 --> 13:08.871
-Nice, for now.
-Nobody's scored higher
on their evaluation.

13:08.871 --> 13:11.499
-Ahhh, yet.
-What's your new charity
you're working with?

13:11.499 --> 13:14.085
-I got a couple things,
you know what? Let's talk
about it over lunch.

13:14.085 --> 13:16.296
-[Gerry]: I gotta get involved.
-[Jody]: Yeah, let's do that.

13:16.296 --> 13:19.549
-I could do lunch,
I'm kind of hungry. Yeah, let's
go have some lunch.

13:19.549 --> 13:23.219
I'll see you at third period.
-Okay, alright.

13:23.219 --> 13:25.305
Paul, good to see you man.

13:25.305 --> 13:29.058
♪ Music ♪

13:29.058 --> 13:31.810
-Mr. Hunt!
-Yeah?

13:31.810 --> 13:34.773
-This is my school and you
will listen.

13:34.773 --> 13:37.816
You're on thin ice here at
Xavier, pal.

13:37.816 --> 13:42.280
-Am I?
-You are uninvolved in student
extracurricular activities Sir.

13:42.280 --> 13:44.491
-I'm the assistant coach of the
five/six girls' basketball team.

13:44.491 --> 13:46.825
-Assistant?
-Yeah.

13:46.825 --> 13:51.205
-Exactly. So I think it's clear,
what you need to do.

13:51.205 --> 13:56.252
-Okay. I'll get you my
resignation by the end of today.

13:56.252 --> 14:00.799
-That's not what I mean. I just
mean you have to try harder.
Crack the whip.

14:00.799 --> 14:03.551
Well, I've been working as hard
as I can and it's obviously not
even close to being good enough.

14:03.551 --> 14:08.264
I'll resign.
-Simon, no, you're one of the
best teachers we have.

14:08.264 --> 14:11.100
-I knew this day would come.
My mom told me there was no
future in science.

14:11.100 --> 14:15.229
She begged me to pursue Spanish.
-You need to respect me.

14:15.229 --> 14:18.274
-Really?
-And between us girls...

14:18.274 --> 14:21.235
You should probably even
ask for a raise.

14:21.235 --> 14:24.656
-Respect you and I get a
raise. I'll think about it.

14:28.993 --> 14:30.911
-Hey Frank, let me grab you
a coffee, buddy.

14:30.911 --> 14:34.332
-Why don't I get you a coffee?
-That's alright, I'll...

14:34.332 --> 14:36.042
-[Frank]: Back it up.

14:39.253 --> 14:41.339
A lot of hot teachers at
this school.

14:41.339 --> 14:44.759
-Yeah, I guess.
-That Lisa's pretty cute.

14:44.759 --> 14:46.761
-Yeah.
-She single?

14:46.761 --> 14:50.849
-She is, yup.
-Might have to tap that.
Milk? Sugar?

14:50.849 --> 14:52.600
-Good. I'll get that.
-I got it.

14:52.600 --> 14:54.352
-Okay.

15:02.193 --> 15:05.238
-Frank, let me get that.
-Don't touch it.

15:05.238 --> 15:06.656
[Frank]: Just don't.

15:09.450 --> 15:12.787
[Bell sounds]
-[Frank]: Almost there.
I don't need any help.

15:12.787 --> 15:16.207
♪ Music ♪

15:16.207 --> 15:19.711
-Alright, Lucy, do you want to
tell us what we were talking
about last class?

15:19.711 --> 15:23.214
And we'll pick it up from there.
-We were talking about ancient
Egypt.

15:23.214 --> 15:26.133
-Ah, yes.
That's right. Egypt!

15:26.133 --> 15:30.430
The pyramids. One of the great
wonders of the world.

15:30.430 --> 15:34.517
Walk like an Egyptian.
Great song of the world.

15:34.517 --> 15:36.060
-How did they build the
pyramids, Sir?

15:36.060 --> 15:39.773
-From the ground up.
Into a pyramid.

15:39.773 --> 15:42.400
That is where the word pyramid
comes from.

15:42.400 --> 15:46.946
They built them with some plans
they had, some schemes. In fact!

15:46.946 --> 15:51.743
The pyramid scheme as we know it
today in the business world,
comes from those same plans.

15:51.743 --> 15:56.623
The tourism industry is huge for
Egypt, still to this day.

15:56.623 --> 16:00.794
-So, the ancient Egyptians
had a tourism industry?

16:00.794 --> 16:02.503
-Yeah.

16:02.503 --> 16:06.257
Business men would fly
over to the pyramids.

16:06.257 --> 16:10.010
In fact, they would use those
pyramids as hotels

16:10.010 --> 16:13.598
for wealthy travelers who were
coming over to see the sphinx.

16:13.598 --> 16:16.016
There you go.

16:16.016 --> 16:22.022
-Fair enough. I think I've
seen all I need to see.

16:23.483 --> 16:24.943
-Already? That's it?

16:24.943 --> 16:28.780
-Yeah, I'll see you
after this class.

16:29.864 --> 16:32.450
-Are you in trouble Sir?
♪ Music ♪

16:32.450 --> 16:35.620
-No, I'm not in trouble.
Why would I be in trouble?

16:42.168 --> 16:45.296
-I'm really nervous. I hope I
did okay. Aren't you nervous?

16:45.296 --> 16:47.882
-Sshhh! Here he comes,
here he comes, here he comes.

16:47.882 --> 16:50.802
-Hey guys. How are you?
-[Gerry]: Good. Hi.

16:50.802 --> 16:54.221
-[Lisa]: Okay.
-Ms. Mason, what can I say?

16:54.221 --> 16:57.475
It's really hard to find
flaws with you.
-Oh.

16:57.475 --> 17:00.603
-You're very socratic,
and structured.

17:00.603 --> 17:02.939
When I sat in your classroom
I couldn't help but thinking:

17:02.939 --> 17:04.649
Wow, that's a great teacher.

17:04.649 --> 17:09.737
-Oh wow. Thank you so much.
It's so nice to hear that.

17:09.737 --> 17:11.906
-Then I sat in on Mr. Duncan's
classes.

17:11.906 --> 17:14.534
-Okay, can we do this
separately? I don't feel
comfortable.

17:14.534 --> 17:20.874
-Please. After sitting in on his
classes, I realized, maybe
you're a little too Socratic.

17:20.874 --> 17:24.293
Maybe a little too structured.
Almost bordering on boring.

17:24.293 --> 17:27.630
-Excuse me?
-He said you're boring.

17:27.630 --> 17:32.426
-Mr. Duncan is a very
exhilarating teacher.
He's very dynamic.

17:32.426 --> 17:35.304
He's not afraid to use his own
personal, real life experiences.

17:35.304 --> 17:37.097
And incorporate them in
his teachings.

17:37.097 --> 17:39.141
Which, by the way, I think
Bethany was in the wrong.

17:39.141 --> 17:41.561
-She was! Thank you. She was.
-Okay, so you think that using

17:41.561 --> 17:45.606
personal experiences is a good
teaching method?

17:45.606 --> 17:47.358
-Connection, it's a connection.
-Absolutely!

17:47.358 --> 17:49.610
I had a chance to look through
one of the students' notebooks.

17:49.610 --> 17:52.739
Maya something or another.
She is just flourishing.

17:52.739 --> 17:55.992
-Well, Maya's smart!
She's a genius.

17:55.992 --> 17:57.785
-I have worked with her.
-[Lisa]: It had nothing to
do with Gerry.

17:57.785 --> 17:59.829
-No, what did I do.
-[Jody]: Here's the thing.

17:59.829 --> 18:04.584
That's neither here nor there,
but I have your evaluations
here.

18:04.584 --> 18:09.338
You both did great.
-But I did better, wow, eights!

18:09.338 --> 18:12.675
Sixes, seven. A ten!
-Sixes.

18:12.675 --> 18:14.677
-You know, you could learn a lot
from a guy like Mr. Duncan.

18:14.677 --> 18:19.098
I know I did.
-Oh, here we go!
Baby, baby, baby.

18:19.098 --> 18:21.392
-[Jody]: I mean, you shouldn't
really be upset at all I mean...

18:21.392 --> 18:23.310
-[Gerry]: That is
unprofessional.

18:23.310 --> 18:25.646
-Gerry, I gotta tell you,
incredible watching you teach.

18:25.646 --> 18:28.482
-Oh, thank you.
-And when you used the:
Walk like and Egyptian.

18:28.482 --> 18:30.610
-When I did that for the kids?

18:30.610 --> 18:33.988
-Yeah! And that's probably how
they carried the bricks to build
the pyramids.

18:33.988 --> 18:36.365
-I think so, I think you're
right. I'm going to use that.

18:36.365 --> 18:37.784
-I didn't know they had
airplanes back then.

18:37.784 --> 18:39.911
That they flew business men
to the pyramids on.

18:39.911 --> 18:41.746
-Yeah, Amelia Earhart.
-Yeah, Amelia Earhart.

18:41.746 --> 18:43.372
I didn't even know
she was Egyptian.

18:43.372 --> 18:44.791
-Well, I don't know if she is.

18:44.791 --> 18:46.459
-Well, you can't stop teaching.
It's a gift.

18:46.459 --> 18:48.795
-Haha, please.
-[Jody]: You're like a machine.

18:48.795 --> 18:51.798
You're a teaching machine.
-Please, it's just natural.

18:51.798 --> 18:54.884
-Here's your lesson plan back.
-How was this?

18:54.884 --> 18:56.803
-I have no clue.
I didn't even open it.

18:56.803 --> 18:59.430
-Get out of here.
-You know what? Who does
a lesson plan?

18:59.430 --> 19:02.100
-I agree!
-I never did one. I was a
teacher for many years.

19:02.100 --> 19:06.020
You know, the world needs
more teachers like you.
-Thank you.

19:06.020 --> 19:08.522
-Hey!

19:08.522 --> 19:11.109
How's the reign of terror going?

19:11.109 --> 19:16.030
-Not well. Maybe you're right
Trudy. Maybe no one is scared
of me.

19:16.030 --> 19:20.493
But maybe it's better to be
liked, than feared.

19:20.493 --> 19:23.412
-Well you're going to have to
work at being liked too.

19:23.412 --> 19:25.790
-I agree with Trudy's mouth.

19:25.790 --> 19:28.960
-I am the vice principal
at this school.

19:28.960 --> 19:32.088
There is a culture of disrespect
and I'm going to root it out.

19:32.088 --> 19:34.214
And I am going to murder
it with policies.

19:34.214 --> 19:35.842
Now, do either of you have
anything disrespectful

19:35.842 --> 19:38.260
to say to me right now?
Because say! I dare you!

19:38.260 --> 19:40.972
Double dog style!

19:42.473 --> 19:44.767
No? Nothing?

19:44.767 --> 19:47.603
I didn't think so.

19:49.939 --> 19:53.567
-That was...a hoot!
[Trudy and Malik laugh]

19:53.567 --> 19:55.611
♪ Music ♪

19:58.364 --> 19:59.907
-[Gerry]: Oh a little social?

20:04.912 --> 20:09.375
Oh, come on. Lisa!
It's not a big deal.

20:09.375 --> 20:11.251
-I'm impressed Duncan.
You did well.

20:11.251 --> 20:13.921
-So maybe my shortcomings
weren't so short.

20:13.921 --> 20:16.465
-Well, still a little short.

20:16.465 --> 20:18.801
-Phys ed, how about phys ed...

20:18.801 --> 20:21.012
Simon! Look!
-[Simon]: Hmm?

20:21.012 --> 20:23.806
-My evaluation, did you hear?
-Whoa!

20:23.806 --> 20:25.975
-Ten out of ten!
-Well done.

20:25.975 --> 20:27.977
-I got a ten on connecting
with the students.

20:27.977 --> 20:31.189
-That's what you do.
-You need help with any
teaching, let me know.

20:31.189 --> 20:33.983
-Yeah, yeah absolutely. We can
get together, have a drink.

20:33.983 --> 20:35.735
Just chat about whatever,
you know?

20:35.735 --> 20:40.489
-Alright, I'm going to take off.
Ha!

20:40.489 --> 20:43.868
Gonna be a good year!
-Gonna be a great year!

20:43.868 --> 20:46.412
♪ Music ♪

20:47.454 --> 20:49.707
[Pouring rain and thunder]

20:58.424 --> 21:01.552
[Pouring rain and thunder]

21:08.142 --> 21:10.394
-See you, Frank!
-See you, Gerry.

21:10.394 --> 21:13.064
